---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import VisualProvingGround from '../../components/VisualProvingGround.tsx';
import ProvingGround from '../../components/ProvingGround.tsx';
---

<Base
  title="The Proving Ground — pathtoAGI"
  description="Play what the frontier models face — first in pure pictures anyone can do, then in the hard numeric worlds where your attempt becomes real human-baseline data for the record."
  ogImage="/media/proving-ground-hero.webp"
>
  <section class="max-w-3xl">
    <p class="eyebrow">The Proving Ground · play the test</p>
    <h1 class="display mt-4 text-4xl sm:text-5xl">You versus the sealed world</h1>
    <p class="lede mt-6">
      This instrument tests whether a mind can find the rule of a world that
      never existed before — without being told what kind of rule to look for.
      It is the one thing that separates a powerful tool from a mind of the
      relevant kind. You can take the test right now. No maths, no account,
      no prerequisite: it starts in pictures.
    </p>
  </section>

  <figure class="mt-8 overflow-hidden border hairline" style="border-radius: 10px; background: var(--color-surface);">
    <img
      src="/media/proving-ground-hero.webp"
      alt="A human hand and a robotic hand reaching toward the same glowing puzzle grid on an antique brass observatory table, star charts behind."
      class="block aspect-[16/9] w-full object-cover"
      loading="eager"
      decoding="async"
    />
    <figcaption class="px-4 py-3 text-xs" style="color: var(--color-faint);">
      Same puzzle, two kinds of mind. The human baseline is not decoration — it
      is verdict gate OG-9, the calibration without which a machine score means
      nothing.
    </figcaption>
  </figure>

  <!-- Universal visual game: no numbers, no prerequisite -->
  <section class="mt-12">
    <div class="max-w-3xl">
      <p class="eyebrow" style="color: var(--color-accent);">Part one · anyone can play</p>
      <h2 class="serif mt-2 text-2xl sm:text-3xl">Three pictures, three ideas</h2>
      <p class="prose mt-4">
        Every hard probe in this record rests on three moves: find a hidden rule
        from a few examples, resist a rule that looks obvious but is secretly
        wrong, and admit when the evidence genuinely can’t decide. Here they are
        with no numbers at all. A child and a professor take the same test — and
        it is the same test, in kind, the machines fail on the hard version.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="mt-8">
      <VisualProvingGround client:visible />
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Advanced numeric worlds -->
  <section class="mt-16">
    <div class="max-w-3xl">
      <p class="eyebrow" style="color: hsl(34 96% 60%);">Part two · the hard version</p>
      <h2 class="serif mt-2 text-2xl sm:text-3xl">The numeric worlds</h2>
      <p class="prose mt-4">
        This is what the frontier models actually faced — the same three ideas,
        but on integer worlds with no visual crutch. Two are revealed and grade
        in your browser. The third is <strong>live and sealed</strong>: no one
        grading you knows the answer, and your attempt becomes real human-baseline
        data the verdict requires (gate OG-9). It is genuinely hard. That is the
        point — and struggling honestly is exactly the data we need.
      </p>
      <p class="mono mt-4 text-xs" style="color: var(--color-faint);">
        Prefer a warm-up? The pictures above carry the same ideas. This part
        rewards comfort with arithmetic — but the sealed world takes any honest
        attempt, in words or numbers.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="mt-8">
      <ProvingGround client:visible />
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="mt-16 max-w-3xl">
    <h2 class="serif text-2xl">Why a game, honestly</h2>
    <p class="prose mt-4">
      This is not gamification for engagement. The verdict cannot move on a
      machine result until competent humans have attempted the identical sealed
      probe, so a score has a scale. Collecting that baseline from strangers, on
      the exact worlds the models faced, graded later by the same mechanical
      grader and published either way, is the honest use of a playable surface.
      You are not the product here; you are a co-author of the baseline.
    </p>
    <p class="mono mt-4 text-xs" style="color: var(--color-faint);">
      Revealed worlds: <a href="/experiments/fcs-synth-world-006/REVEAL.md" class="hover:underline" style="color: var(--color-accent);">world-006</a>,
      <a href="/experiments/fcs-synth-world-005/REVEAL.md" class="hover:underline" style="color: var(--color-accent);">world-005</a>.
      Live sealed world: <a href="/runs/" class="hover:underline" style="color: var(--color-accent);">world-003</a>.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Netlify form registration (hidden): captures Level-3 human-baseline attempts -->
  <form name="human-baseline-world-003" netlify netlify-honeypot="bot-field" hidden>
    <input type="text" name="bot-field" />
    <textarea name="attempt"></textarea>
  </form>
</Base>
